Problem 1

Load the tidyverse package

library(tidyverse)

In this problem you will work with vehicle fuel economy data from the US EPA (Environmental Protection Agency), ranging from 1985-2015.

Read the data using the code below:

vehicles <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/reisanar/datasets/master/vehicles.csv")

-- Column specification ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
cols(
  id = col_double(),
  make = col_character(),
  model = col_character(),
  year = col_double(),
  class = col_character(),
  trans = col_character(),
  drive = col_character(),
  cyl = col_double(),
  displ = col_double(),
  fuel = col_character(),
  hwy = col_double(),
  cty = col_double()
)
Variable Description
id Unique EPA identifier
make Manufacturer
model Model name
year Model year
class EPA vehicle size class
trans Transmission
drive Drive train
cyl Number of cylinders
displ Engine displacement, in litres
fuel Fuel type
hwy Highway fuel economy, in mpg
cty City fuel economy, in mpg
  1. (6 points) Select the different manufacturers (makes) of the cars in this data set. Save this vector in a variable called makes
makes <- vehicles %>%
  group_by(make) %>%
  summarise(count = n_distinct(make)) %>%
  select(make)
makes
  1. (6 points) Can you determine how many different car manufacturers are represented by the data set?
nrow(makes)
[1] 128
  1. (6 points) Filter the data set for vehicles manufactured in 1998.
vehicles %>%
  filter(year == 1998)
  1. (8 points) Mutate the 1998 cars data frame to add a column average that has the average gas mileage (between city and highway MPG) for each car
vehicles %>%
  filter(year == 1998) %>%
  mutate(average = (hwy + cty)/2)
  1. (8 points) Of all vehicles, what is the vehicle ID of the vehicle with the worst highway MPG?
vehicles %>%
  filter(hwy == min(hwy)) %>%
  select(id, hwy)
  1. (8 points) Which 2013 Acura model has the best highway MPG? Which 2015 Honda model has the best highway MPG?
vehicles %>%
  filter(year == 2013, make == "Acura") %>%
  filter(hwy == max(hwy)) %>%
  select(make, model, hwy)
vehicles %>%
  filter(year == 2015, make == "Honda") %>%
  filter(hwy == max(hwy)) %>%
  select(make, model, hwy)

Problem 2

Load the nycflights13 packages.

library(nycflights13)

Use the flights dataframe to answer the following questions.

  1. (6 points) Find all flights headed to TPA, and select only the origin, destination, and the departure time.
flights %>%
  filter(dest == "TPA") %>%
  select(origin, dest, dep_time)
  1. (6 points) Consider flights from JFK to MCO. What was the average, minimum, and maximum air time of those flights?
flights %>%
  filter(origin == "JFK", dest == "MCO") %>%
  summarise(ave = mean(air_time, na.rm = TRUE), minimum = min(air_time, na.rm = TRUE), maximum = max(air_time, na.rm = TRUE))
  1. (6 points) What was the average departure delay in each month? Save this as a data frame dep_delay_by_month. (Hint: you may have to perform a grouping operation then summarizing your data).
dep_delay_by_month <- flights %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(ave = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
dep_delay_by_month
  1. (8 points) Which month had the greatest average departure delay?
dep_delay_by_month %>%
  filter(ave == max(ave))
  1. (8 points) To which destinations were the average arrival delays the highest?
flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(ave = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  arrange(desc(ave))
  1. (8 points) Which airline had the smallest average arrival delay?
flights %>%
  group_by(carrier) %>%
  summarise(ave = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(ave == min(ave))
  1. (8 points) Find all flights that were operated by United, American, or Delta.
filter(flights, carrier == "UA" | carrier == "AA" | carrier == "DL")
  1. (8 points) Find all the flights (if any) headed to Orlando, Tampa, or Miami with a scheduled departure time later than 8:00 PM.
flights %>%
  filter(dest == "ORL" | dest == "TPA" | dest == "MIA", sched_dep_time > 2000) %>%
  arrange(dep_time)
